AGI - The AGI Editors' Meeting has returned to meet the next day of the meeting with the company's advisor and the manager. The Assembly took note of the answer with which the company and the director stated that "Eni S.p.A. received a non-binding event of unsolicited interest by a subject interested in AGI Spa whose content is subject to confidentiality commitments. A preliminary interlocution is followed. Today there is no negotiation in progress and therefore no agreement has been signed".
&nbsp;
The Cdr of the AGI proclaims from midnight today (from 00.01 on Wednesday 27 March) another two days of strike of the package of five deliberated unanimously by the drafting assembly of 18 March. The battle against sale to the Angelucci group of the AGI, tested that by its nature is now impartial and autonomous by political conditioning, is a battle for the occupational stability of journalists and polygraphs; but even more is a battle to defend the primary information role of the press agencies that have in their dna independence and pluralism. The Board recalls that the possible transfer of AGI is now under observation of the European Union, in the light of the Law on Media Freedom (Media freedom act), a measure "relevant - the European Commission has asserted - for any situation of media fusion".
&nbsp;
The Board is evaluating all the actions to be put in place to avoid the sale of AGI and the agency can remain under a publisher who has always guaranteed autonomy and independence. In this context, the unanimity Assembly entrusts the CoR with a new four-day strike package to be used in the times and arrangements that the CoR will feel more appropriate. The Board asked for a meeting with the Undersecretary of the Presidency of the Council with a delegation to Editorial, Alberto Barachini, who has the responsibility for relations with the press agencies and support for primary information.

